Comment: 7:20 what Are ^ 2 means How much of the variance in the y data can be explained by taking the x data into a count . Taking the x data into account here means shifting the line around which we measure the variance from just being a flat line in the middle of the y data to being the regression line with respect to x data . Are ^ 2 = variance ( around flat line variance around regression line ) / variance around flat line The higher Are ^ 2 is , means the variance around the regression line is lower and we have a better fit stronger correlation between the variables 12:20 predicting variable based on two variables instead of one . Two variables on the z and x axis , the prediction is the y axis . In this case we fit a plane to the data not a line . The plane has 3 parameters . 13:30 we fit a plane 14:20 if the tail length variable in the z axis is n ’ t useful doesn ’ t ( give a higher Are ^ 2 ) then the least squares method will give it a coefficient of 0. Equations with more parameters won ’ t make the sum of squares around the fit worse than an equation with fewer parameters . Least squares will make parameters that make Are ^ 2 around the fit worse have 0 coef I cient . So having more parameters won ’ t make our are ^ 2 worse , but it could make it better due to random chance . Without ( there actually being a co relation ) 15:50 we report an adjusted Are ^ 2 that scales Are ^ 2 by the number of params in the model 16:0 Are ^ 2 needs a p value To do : Continue is A

Comment: Great video ! But I still have a question about why we square the residuals . Squaring seems arbitrary . The video says that it is a) so that all the negative residuals become positive , and b) to emphasise the bigger residuals . Those are good answers . But why do we square them particularly , as opposed to raising them to the th 4 power ? Or the th6 ? Or to the power of any even number ? All these answers would give you positive residuals and emphasise the bigger numbers , which means that squaring the residuals is a bit arbitrary . I would not mind this ordinarily . Hey , it all works , right ? But maths is not supposed to be arbitrary . And if the whole subject of statistics and even machine learning is based on squaring residuals , might we come up with different answers if we raise to a different power ?
